steps.instruction:
For a more step by step guide go [here](https://www.kingarthurflour.com/blog/2013/02/19/danish-pastry-beauty-or-the-beast)

#### Ingredients 
- Have the unsalted butter reach room temp
- If you are using salted butter, then reduce the 2.5 teaspoons of salt that is for the dough to 1.5 teaspoons of salt
- You can increased cardamon to 1 teaspoon if you really like it
- You can replace the cottage cheese with ricotta cheese if you like 

### Making the Dough
1. Cut 1/4 inch off the end of each of the 4 sticks of butter in the pound; you'll have 2 tablespoons of butter, set them aside
2. In a large bowl, whisk together 5.5 cups of flour, 1/3 cup of sugar,  4 teaspoons of instant yeast, 2.5 teaspoons of salt, and 1/2 teaspoons of cardamom
3. Add the 2 tablespoons of cold butter
4. Work the butter in with your hands till no lumps remain 
5. Add the 1 teaspoon of vanilla, 1 cup of milk, and 2 eggs.
6. Mix and knead to make a cohesive, but still sticky dough
7. Scrape the dough into a ball and transfer it to a floured work surface
8. Cover it with plastic wrap, let it rest for 10 minutes
9. Cut each stick of butter in half *lengthwise*, to make 8 long rectangle.
10. On a piece of floured parchment or plastic wrap, line up 4 of the butter pieces side by side, to form a rectangle.
11. Sprinkle lightly with flour, and cover with another piece of parchment or plastic wrap 
12. Gently pound and roll and roll the butter until it's about 6x9 inches
13. The pieces may or may not meld together
14. Repeat with the remaining 4 pieces of butter. You should now have two butter rectangles, about 6x9 inch each
15. Roll the dough into rectangle about 12 inches wide and 24 inches long
16. Place one of the butter pieces onto the center third of the dough. Fold one side over the butter to cover it
17. Place the other butter piece atop the folded-over dough, and then fold the remaining dough up over it. You now have a rectangle "packet" of dough enclosed butter. Pinch the open ends and side closed
18. Turn the dough 90 degrees, Roll the dough into a 10x24 inch rectangle. Fold each side into the center; then fold one side over the other to make a rectangle packer about 6x10 inches
19. Dust the surface of the dough with flour, wrap it in plastic wrap, and chill in the fridge for about 20 minutes
20. Remove the dough from the fridge, and again toll it into a rectangle about 10x24 inches.
21. Fold it into a packet as you did when you turned it 90 degrees, it'll be about 7x12 inches.
22. Roll one final time, fold into a packet, and flour the dough lightly
23. Wrap loosely in plastic, and chill it for 2 hours, or up to 16 hours


### Cheese Filling
1. Combine 1/2 cup of cream cheese, 1/2 cup of cottage cheese (or ricotta cheese), 3 tablespoons of granulated sugar, 1 large egg, 1/4 salt


### Fruit Filling
1. Just use Jam c:


### Glaze
1. Whisk the 1.5 cups of powdered sugar, 2 tablespoons of milk and a pinch of salt


### Shaping and Filling
2. Stir until smooth 
3. Remove the dough from the fridge, unwrap it, cut off one third
4. Return the remaining 2/3 back to the fridge
5. Divide the dough into 12 pieces
6. Roll each into a smooth ball, then flatten the balls into 3" to 3.5" rounds, making the center thinner than the edges
7. You want to build up a slight wall of dough all around the circumference; this will help hold the filling. Place the rounds on a parchment-lined or lightly greased baking sheet.
8. Working with one-half of the remaining dough at a time, repeat the process
9. Cover the Danish lightly with greased plastic wrap, and let them rise for about 1 hour; they'll become slightly puffy. Towards the end of the rising time, preheat the oven to 400F
10. Use your fingers to press the centers of the dough rounds as flat as possible, leaving the "sidewalls" puffed
11. Spoon a slightly heaping measuring teaspoon of filling into the well of each round
12. Brush the exposed edges of pastry with the egg/water topping
13. Bake the pastries for 15 to 18 minutes, until they're golden brown
14. Remove them from the oven, and transfer to a rack
15. Glaze and serve immediately; or wait until they cool, then glaze


#### Tips
- Why all the rolling and folding? That's what gives Danish pastry its flaky layers. Each time you roll, fold, and roll again, you're creating more and thinner layers of butter  128 layers, if you do the four "turns" indicated in the directions
- Feel free to serve pastries warm, right out of the oven; if you glaze them right away the glaze may melt and spread a bit, but they'll be delicious
